body:
Can you attach an example that shows the issue?  (Must be openly licensed, ideally in test_regress format.)

I started chasing this down with an error in the statement:

    wire [839:0] large;
    wire [103:0] value;

    // ...

    assign large = { {(840-104){1'b0}}, value };

In the VCD file, bit 124 was set in `large` following this assignment.  When I then applied bit-wise operations on `large`, bits were getting set that shouldn't have been.

I then managed to chase this back further to the function two clock cycles before,

    function [W-1:0] reverse(input [W-1:0] val);
        integer i;
    begin
        for(i=0; i<W; i=i+1)
            reverse[W-1-i] = val[i];    
    end endfunction

The purpose of this function is to reverse the bits in the input `val` provided.  Key to this bug is that the function never initializes all of `reverse`.  It shouldn't need to, since all of the 104 bits produced by the function are initialized internally within the function.  However, because Verilator maps large vectors to 32-bit words in C/C++, what happens is that the upper (128-104=) 24 bits are not getting initialized.  These bits then contribute to the following logic in ... bad ways.  Specifically, I'm shifting and then ORing this value into an 840-bit gearbox, and some of the other (840-104) bits are getting set in that gearbox--thus breaking the rest of the algorithm.

For now I'm testing a fix whereby I set `reverse=0` prior to the for loop as a work around.

_What 'verilator --version' are you using?  Did you try it with the git master version?_

I tested with `Verilator 5.003 devel rev v5.002-41-g04f68cbd9`

_What OS and distribution are you using?_

Linux Ubuntu

_May we assist you in trying to fix this in Verilator yourself?_

<Gasp!>  Frankly, I wouldn't know where to start.
